07260nam a22010455i 9783110770162DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021951716  a97831107701627 a10.1515/97831107701622doi  a(DE-B1597)611982  a(OCoLC)1312725728  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a910.914200aIslands in Geography, Law, and Literature :bA Cross-Disciplinary Journey /ced. by Chiara Battisti, Sidia Fiorato, Matteo Nicolini, Thomas Perrin. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VI, 254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw & Literature ,x2191-8457 ;v2000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIsland-ness: A ‘New Province’ of Cross-Disciplinary Research -- tPart One: Remote Islands as Fictional Landscapes -- tThe Island Metaphor in Literature and Law -- tBacon’s New Atlantis and the Crisis of Western Liberalism -- tThe Unbelievable History of Rose Island, a Micronation -- tPart Two: Geographical Imaginaries: Law, Literature and Ecological Crises -- tHumanistic Enchantment: A Durational Reading of Imagined Adaptations -- tAldous Huxley’s Island(ness): Politics and Ecology -- tCommon Law, Environmental Titles, and Remote Islands in Times of Climate Change -- tJ. M. Barrie’s Peter Pan and the Island of the Self -- tPart Three: Organising Remoteness: Legal and Institutional Perspectives -- tIslands and Territorial Cooperation in the European Union: Overview and Outlooks -- tA Geopolitical Study of the Mediterranean Insularity: Islands as Outposts of the European Union on the Most Intense Fracture Line in the World -- tFaraway, so Close: Islands and Constitutional Remoteness in the Nordic Countries -- tPart Four: Outlining Insular Identity: Some Case Studies -- tFrom Islands-of-Islands to the Archipelago: Re-appropriating Relatedness in the Belep Islands (Kanaky-New Caledonia) -- tIn Memory of Madama Butterfly: An Insular View on an International Convention -- t‘Jolly Good Show. Like The Coral Island’ – Golding’s Lord Of The Flies in the Perspective of Law and Literature -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection explores the heterogeneous places we have traditionally been taught to term ‘islands.’ It stages a conversation on the very idea of ‘island-ness’, thus contributing to a new field of research at the crossroads of law, geography, literature, urban planning, politics, arts, and cultural studies. The contributions to this volume discuss the notion of island-ness as a device triggering the imagination, triggering narratives and representations in different creative fields; they explore the interactions between legal, socio-political, and fictional approaches to remoteness and the ‘state of insularity,’ policy responses to both remoteness and boundaries on different scales, and the insular legal framing of geographical remoteness. The product of a cross-disciplinary exchange on islands, this edited volume will be of great interest to those working in the fields of Island Studies, as well as literary studies scholars, geographers, and legal scholars.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aIslands in literature. 0aIslandsxLaw and legislation. 0aIslandsxSocial aspects.  aIsland Studies.  aLaw and Geography.  aLaw and the Humanities.1 aBattisti, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattisti, Chiara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBezrucka, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpi, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCostantini, Cristina, econtr